The code in Java's modinv function is a bit tricky. Let me see:

The Java code for modinv:

static long modinv(long a, int m) {
    long b = m;
    long u = 1;
    long v = 0;
    long tmp = 0;
    while (b > 0) {
        long t = a / b;
        a -= t * b;
        tmp = a;
        a = b;
        b = tmp; u -= t * v;
        tmp = u;
        u = v;
        v = tmp;
    } u %= m;
    if (u < 0) u += m;
    return u;
} Hmm, this is the extended Euclidean algorithm.

Wait, but in the code above, the variables are being updated in each iteration. Let me check the steps:

The code in Java:

long t = a / b;

a -= t * b;

tmp = a;

a = b;

b = tmp; Then, the same for u and v.

Wait, in the code above, the Fortran code: t = a / b

a = a - t*b → which is the same as a mod b?

If so, change it to the opposite, and count the changes. Wait, in the Java code, the first loop for a1 is:

for (int i = 1; i < x.length(); i++) {
    if (a.charAt(i) == a.charAt(i - 1)) {
        if (a.charAt(i) == '1') a.setCharAt(i, '0');
        else a.setCharAt(i, '0'); // Wait, no, the code says else set to '1'? Wait, let me check: Wait, the code says:

if (a.charAt(i) == '1') a.setCharAt(i, '0');
else a.setCharAt(i, '1'); Wait, no, the code is:

if (a.charAt(i) == a.charAt(i-1)), then:

if the current character is '1', set to '0', else set to '1'.

If so, change the previous character to the opposite, and count the change. Wait, in the code for a2:

for (int i = x.length() - 1; i > 0; i--) {
    if (b.charAt(i) == b.charAt(i - 1)) {
        if (b.charAt(i - 1) == '1') b.setCharAt(i - 1, '0');
        else b.setCharAt(i - 1, '1');
        a2++;
    }
}

So here, when the current character (i) and previous (i-1) are same, we change the previous (i-1) to the opposite. So the change is made to the previous character, not the current one. So the direction is different.

Wait, let me see:

Java's x.length() is the length. So in Java, the indices go from 0 to length-1. So the loop starts at i = length-1 (the last character), and goes down to i=1 (since i>0). So in Fortran, the loop would be from i = len down to 2 (since in Fortran, the first character is 1, last is len). Wait, in the Java code for a2:

for (int i = x.length() -1; i>0; i--):

Alternatively, perhaps in the second scenario (a2), the code is processing from the end towards the start, changing the previous character (i-1) when the current (i) and previous are the same. Wait, in the Java code for a2:

if (b.charAt(i) == b.charAt(i-1)), then change the (i-1)th character. Wait, in the code:

if (b.charAt(i) == b.charAt(i-1)), then:

if (b.charAt(i-1) is '1', set to '0', else '1'.

Because in Java, the index is i (starting from 1 to n-1?), let me check: In Java's code for q:

for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
    q[i] = (q[i-1] + modinv(i+1, mod)) % mod;
} Wait, the loop runs from i=1 to i < n (so up to i = n-1).

Wait, let me recheck:

Java's code for q[i] (where i starts at 1) uses modinv(i+1, mod). So when i=1 (Java's index), it's modinv(2, mod). In Fortran's i=2 (since q(2) corresponds to Java's q[1]), the term is modinv(2, mod). So yes, the Fortran code is correct. Then, the ans is computed as:

ans = 0

do i = 1, n

    val = (q(i) + q(n - i) - 1) * a(i)

    val = mod(val, mod)

    val = mod(val * p, mod)

    ans = mod(ans + val, mod)

end do

Wait, in Java's code:

for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {

    long val = q[i] + q[n - i -1] -1;

    val *= a[i];

    val %= mod;

    val *= p;

    val %= mod;

    ans += val;

    ans %= mod;

}

So in Java, for each i from 0 to n-1 (0-based), the terms are q[i] and q[n - i -1].
